He was just telling me

800
00:41:07,696 --> 00:41:09,571
that all our plumbing
works backwards.

801
00:41:09,611 --> 00:41:10,768
That's right.

802
00:41:10,848 --> 00:41:12,683
An important thing
to remember is

803
00:41:12,763 --> 00:41:15,557
you have to flush up.
Until tomorrow night.

804
00:41:15,637 --> 00:41:17,472
What's tomorrow night?
Where's he going?

805
00:41:17,552 --> 00:41:18,909
Don't forget Tuesday.

806
00:41:18,989 --> 00:41:21,543
What's he doing
in the bedroom?

807
00:41:41,695 --> 00:41:44,848
That nut went out
the window.

808
00:41:51,034 --> 00:41:51,912
Hello.

809
00:41:51,991 --> 00:41:53,348
Hello, Mother?
It's me.

810
00:41:53,428 --> 00:41:55,743
Did you hear
what I said?

811
00:41:55,823 --> 00:41:56,900
Nothing's wrong.

812
00:41:56,980 --> 00:42:00,571
I just want to confirm
our Tuesday night dinner date.

813
00:42:00,651 --> 00:42:02,528
At 2:00
in the morning?

814
00:42:02,567 --> 00:42:04,244
I want to be sure
you'll come.

815
00:42:04,323 --> 00:42:06,039
At 2:00
in the morning?

816
00:42:06,079 --> 00:42:08,912
And, Mother, wear something
gay and frivolous.

817
00:42:08,952 --> 00:42:11,387
Buy a new dress.

818
00:42:11,466 --> 00:42:13,502
At 2:00
in the morning?

819
00:42:13,581 --> 00:42:15,975
I'll call you
tomorrow. Bye.

820
00:42:17,253 --> 00:42:18,649
Who you waving at?

821
00:42:18,689 --> 00:42:20,485
Him.

822
00:42:52,491 --> 00:42:54,765
I decided to meet you here
every day.

823
00:42:54,805 --> 00:42:57,639
It takes you so long
to climb the stairs,

824
00:42:57,678 --> 00:42:59,554
and I can't wait for you.

825
00:42:59,594 --> 00:43:01,948
The bus driver will think
you're my mother.

826
00:43:09,930 --> 00:43:11,765
Have you
an Aunt Fern?

827
00:43:11,845 --> 00:43:14,159
She sent us
a check today.

828
00:43:14,239 --> 00:43:17,033
Boy, do you have
a cheap Aunt Fern.

829
00:43:17,113 --> 00:43:18,948
I'll write
and tell her.

830
00:43:19,028 --> 00:43:20,864
Your mother called
from Philly.

831
00:43:20,943 --> 00:43:23,737
She and your father
are coming up,

832
00:43:23,817 --> 00:43:27,089
and your sister has
a new boyfriend from Rutgers.

833
00:43:27,169 --> 00:43:29,963
He has acne, and
they all hate him,

834
00:43:30,043 --> 00:43:31,399
including
your sister.

835
00:43:31,479 --> 00:43:33,314
Did you miss me
today?

836
00:43:33,395 --> 00:43:34,272
No.

837
00:43:34,352 --> 00:43:35,231
Why not?

838
00:43:35,310 --> 00:43:36,666
You called eight times.

839
00:43:36,746 --> 00:43:39,540
I don't talk to you
that much when I'm home.

840
00:43:39,620 --> 00:43:42,414
Grouch. How'd it go
in court today?

841
00:43:42,493 --> 00:43:43,850
Gump or Birnbaum?

842
00:43:43,930 --> 00:43:44,808
Birnbaum.

843
00:43:44,887 --> 00:43:46,244
You won? Oh, Paul!

844
00:43:46,324 --> 00:43:47,721
Oh, I'm so proud.

845
00:43:49,238 --> 00:43:50,515
Aren't you happy?

846
00:43:50,595 --> 00:43:52,430
We were awarded
6 cents.

847
00:43:52,510 --> 00:43:54,824
You have to be
awarded something,

848
00:43:54,904 --> 00:43:57,698
so the court made it
6 cents.

849
00:43:57,778 --> 00:43:59,613
How much do you get?

850
00:43:59,693 --> 00:44:01,529
Birnbaum gets
the whole 6 cents.

851
00:44:01,609 --> 00:44:02,966
From here on in,

852
00:44:03,045 --> 00:44:06,796
I get the cases that come in
for a dime or under.

853
00:44:10,388 --> 00:44:11,745
Grouch,
grouch, grouch.

854
00:44:11,825 --> 00:44:14,618
You weren't that grouchy
under the covers.

855
00:44:14,698 --> 00:44:18,928
Do you have to carry on a personal
conversation with me on the stairs?

856
00:44:19,008 --> 00:44:20,365
What's wrong with it?

857
00:44:20,444 --> 00:44:22,759
Everybody knows
the intimate details of your life.

858
00:44:22,838 --> 00:44:25,632
I ring the bell, and suddenly
we're on the air.

859
00:44:25,712 --> 00:44:28,026
I better make you
a drink.

860
00:44:28,106 --> 00:44:30,421
You're supposed to be
charming tonight.

861
00:44:30,501 --> 00:44:33,294
This little dinner
you have planned for tonight

862
00:44:33,375 --> 00:44:36,168
has got fiasco
written all over it.

863
00:44:36,247 --> 00:44:39,041
Maybe they have
a lot in common.

864
00:44:39,121 --> 00:44:40,478
Are you kidding?

865
00:44:40,558 --> 00:44:41,595
Your mother?

866
00:44:41,674 --> 00:44:44,468
That quiet, dainty
little woman from New Jersey

867
00:44:44,548 --> 00:44:46,862
and the Count
of Monte Cristo?

868
00:44:46,942 --> 00:44:47,820
You must be kidding.

869
00:44:47,900 --> 00:44:48,738
Why?

870
00:44:48,779 --> 00:44:50,175
You've seen
his apartment.

871
00:44:50,214 --> 00:44:52,570
He wears Japanese kimonos
and sleeps on rugs.

872
00:44:52,609 --> 00:44:55,402
Your mother wears a hair net
and sleeps on a board.

873
00:44:55,482 --> 00:44:56,919
Boof.

874
00:45:05,978 --> 00:45:07,814
Maybe we could help her.

875
00:45:07,894 --> 00:45:09,729
We don't have
to introduce her

876
00:45:09,809 --> 00:45:12,123
as my dull, 52-year-old,
housewife mother.

877
00:45:12,203 --> 00:45:14,518
That wasn't the exact wording
I had planned.

878
00:45:14,598 --> 00:45:16,434
What did you have
in mind?

879
00:45:16,514 --> 00:45:17,870
Something more glamorous.

880
00:45:17,950 --> 00:45:19,107
Former actress.

881
00:45:20,145 --> 00:45:22,459
You know, of course,
that she was in

882
00:45:22,539 --> 00:45:24,375
The Man
Who Came To Dinner.

883
00:45:24,454 --> 00:45:26,770
Your mother? Where?
The East Orange Women's Club?

884
00:45:26,849 --> 00:45:29,164
On Broadway. She was in
the original company

885
00:45:29,243 --> 00:45:30,680
of Strange Interlude,

886
00:45:30,760 --> 00:45:33,074
and she had
a small singing part

887
00:45:33,114 --> 00:45:34,511
in Knickerbocker Holiday.

888
00:45:34,591 --> 00:45:35,948
Are you serious?

889
00:45:35,988 --> 00:45:38,382
Cross my heart.

890
00:45:40,458 --> 00:45:41,814
Your mother an actress?

891
00:45:41,893 --> 00:45:42,812
Yeah.

892
00:45:44,328 --> 00:45:46,124
You never told me this.

893
00:45:46,204 --> 00:45:48,518
Why didn't you
ever tell me?

894
00:45:48,598 --> 00:45:50,913
I didn't think
you'd be interested.

895
00:45:50,993 --> 00:45:52,350
That's fascinating.

896
00:45:52,430 --> 00:45:54,584
I can't get over that.

897
00:45:56,420 --> 00:45:57,777
See?
Now you're interested.

898
00:45:57,857 --> 00:45:59,214
It's a lie.

899
00:45:59,294 --> 00:46:00,650
Every bit of it.

900
00:46:00,729 --> 00:46:02,606
I'm going to control
myself.

901
00:46:25,791 --> 00:46:26,670
Hello, Mom.

902
00:46:26,749 --> 00:46:27,946
Are you
all right?

903
00:46:28,026 --> 00:46:28,904
Paul...

904
00:46:28,984 --> 00:46:29,861
Yes, Mom.

905
00:46:29,942 --> 00:46:32,256
In my handbag...
are some pink pills.

906
00:46:32,336 --> 00:46:33,533
Pink pills? Right.

907
00:46:33,613 --> 00:46:36,406
I'll be all right.
I'm a little out of breath.

908
00:46:36,486 --> 00:46:38,321
I'll get you
something to drink.

909
00:46:38,401 --> 00:46:40,716
I had to park
three blocks away.

910
00:46:40,796 --> 00:46:43,509
It started to rain, so I ran
the last two blocks.

911
00:46:43,589 --> 00:46:46,064
Then my heel got caught in
the subway grating.

912
00:46:46,144 --> 00:46:48,937
When I pulled my foot out,
I stepped in a puddle.

913
00:46:49,017 --> 00:46:51,491
Then a cab went by and
splashed my stockings.

914
00:46:51,571 --> 00:46:53,885
If the hardware
store downstairs was open,

915
00:46:53,966 --> 00:46:56,759
I was going to buy a knife
and kill myself.

916
00:46:56,838 --> 00:46:57,717
Drink this.

917
00:46:57,797 --> 00:46:59,154
Here's your pill,
Mom.

918
00:47:03,383 --> 00:47:05,697
A martini
to wash down a pill.

919
00:47:05,777 --> 00:47:07,294
It'll make you
feel better.

920
00:47:07,374 --> 00:47:09,848
A martini I had at
home made me sick.

921
00:47:09,928 --> 00:47:11,445
That's what
the pill's for.

922
00:47:11,524 --> 00:47:13,041
Let me help you
inside.

923
00:47:13,121 --> 00:47:15,595
You need food. I'll get you
an hors d'oeuvre.

924
00:47:15,674 --> 00:47:16,553
No, thanks.

925
00:47:16,632 --> 00:47:18,947
It's just sour cream
and blue cheese.

926
00:47:19,026 --> 00:47:20,862
I wish you hadn't
said that.

927
00:47:20,942 --> 00:47:22,139
Like to lie down?

928
00:47:22,219 --> 00:47:25,173
No, thanks, dear.
I can't lie down without my board.

929
00:47:25,252 --> 00:47:29,003
Right now, all I want to do is
see the apartment.

930
00:47:29,083 --> 00:47:30,919
Well, then...
help you up.

931
00:47:30,998 --> 00:47:32,036
Up.

932
00:47:37,384 --> 00:47:38,341
Corie.

933
00:47:39,499 --> 00:47:40,377
Corie!

934
00:47:40,457 --> 00:47:41,653
Do you like it?

935
00:47:41,733 --> 00:47:42,891
Like it?

936
00:47:42,970 --> 00:47:43,849
Tsk.

937
00:47:46,163 --> 00:47:47,799
It's magnificent.

938
00:47:49,436 --> 00:47:50,353
Oh...

939
00:47:51,351 --> 00:47:54,464
Oh. And you did it all
by yourself.

940
00:47:54,544 --> 00:47:56,379
Mr. Velasco gave me
some ideas.

941
00:47:56,459 --> 00:47:57,657
- Who?
- Our decorator.

942
00:47:57,736 --> 00:48:00,290
He comes in through the window
once a week.

943
00:48:00,330 --> 00:48:02,405
Oh, the man
that lives upstairs.

944
00:48:02,485 --> 00:48:04,800
Oh, you've heard
about him, eh?

945
00:48:04,879 --> 00:48:07,673
Yes. Corie had me on the phone for
two hours yesterday.

946
00:48:07,753 --> 00:48:10,067
Did you know he's been married
four times?

947
00:48:10,147 --> 00:48:12,941
Yes. If I were you,
I'd sleep with a gun.

948
00:48:14,896 --> 00:48:15,774
Mother...

949
00:48:15,853 --> 00:48:18,169
See, we did
get the bed in.

950
00:48:18,248 --> 00:48:19,765
Yes. Just fits,
doesn't it?

951
00:48:19,845 --> 00:48:22,159
Just. We have to
turn in unison.

952
00:48:22,239 --> 00:48:23,596
Well, I must admit,

953
00:48:23,676 --> 00:48:26,389
I never expected
anything like this.

954
00:48:27,427 --> 00:48:29,103
Can't wait to see
the expression

955
00:48:29,182 --> 00:48:31,018
on your parents'
faces tonight, Paul.

956
00:48:31,098 --> 00:48:32,933
I beg your...
my what?

957
00:48:33,013 --> 00:48:34,211
Your mother
and father.

958
00:48:34,290 --> 00:48:35,807
We're dining
with them tonight.

959
00:48:35,887 --> 00:48:37,643
Isn't that what
you said, Corie?

960
00:48:37,722 --> 00:48:39,558
Is that what
you told her?

961
00:48:39,638 --> 00:48:42,432
If I said you had a blind date
with Mr. Velasco,

962
00:48:42,511 --> 00:48:44,985
I couldn't have blasted you
out of the house.

963
00:48:45,065 --> 00:48:46,582
Blind date
with Mr. Velas...

964
00:48:46,661 --> 00:48:48,178
The man that
lives upst...

965
00:48:48,258 --> 00:48:49,136
Good God.

966
00:48:49,216 --> 00:48:50,732
What's all the panic,
Mother?

967
00:48:50,812 --> 00:48:52,168
He's just a man.

968
00:48:52,249 --> 00:48:54,085
My accountant
is just a man.

969
00:48:54,164 --> 00:48:56,479
You make him sound like
Douglas Fairbanks.

970
00:48:56,558 --> 00:48:59,352
He looks nothing
like Douglas Fairbanks, does he, Paul?

971
00:48:59,392 --> 00:49:01,228
No. He just
jumps like him.

972
00:49:01,268 --> 00:49:03,781
Come on. You're going to have
a marvelous evening.

973
00:49:03,821 --> 00:49:05,059
Come on where?

974
00:49:05,098 --> 00:49:06,655
To Mr. Velasco's
for cocktails.

975
00:49:06,695 --> 00:49:07,932
I'm not even dressed.

976
00:49:07,972 --> 00:49:09,208
You look fine.

977
00:49:09,288 --> 00:49:11,763
For Paul's parents
I just wanted to look clean.

978
00:49:11,803 --> 00:49:13,359
He'll think
I'm a nurse.

979
00:49:13,399 --> 00:49:14,956
He'll think you're very
interesting.

980
00:49:15,035 --> 00:49:16,233
How's my hair?

981
00:49:16,273 --> 00:49:18,627
Fine. Push it up
a bit in back.

982
00:49:18,667 --> 00:49:21,021
Paul, is something
wrong with my hair?

983
00:49:22,657 --> 00:49:25,012
Mother, just try to go along
with everything.

984
00:49:25,052 --> 00:49:27,406
What do you mean?
Where are we going?

985
00:49:27,446 --> 00:49:29,003
Be one
of the fellows.

986
00:49:29,042 --> 00:49:30,280
One of what fellows?

987
00:49:30,320 --> 00:49:31,556
Should I go first?

988
00:49:31,596 --> 00:49:32,514
Go where?

989
00:49:32,554 --> 00:49:34,908
Up there. That's where
the birdman lives.

990
00:49:34,948 --> 00:49:35,906
Good Lord.

991
00:49:36,984 --> 00:49:37,862
Oh...

992
00:49:37,941 --> 00:49:40,257
Go on, Paul.
It's all right, Mother.

993
00:49:40,336 --> 00:49:41,973
I'll be right
behind you.

994
00:49:42,132 --> 00:49:42,930
Oh!

995
00:49:42,970 --> 00:49:44,606
Mother, are you
all right?

996
00:49:44,686 --> 00:49:47,000
Oh, my! You should've
told me about this.

997
00:49:47,081 --> 00:49:48,596
I'd have gone
into training.

998
00:49:48,676 --> 00:49:50,712
I've got you.
Paul, pull her up.

999
00:49:50,752 --> 00:49:51,988
Give me your hand.

1000
00:49:52,028 --> 00:49:53,266
You're pulling
my arm!

1001
00:49:53,306 --> 00:49:54,543
Stop pulling
her arm!

1002
00:49:54,583 --> 00:49:56,139
I'm not pulling.
I'm helping.

1003
00:49:56,179 --> 00:49:57,096
Ohh!

1004
00:49:58,414 --> 00:49:59,491
Thank you.

1005
00:49:59,571 --> 00:50:02,324
Oh! Isn't this wild?
What do you think, Mother?

1006
00:50:02,404 --> 00:50:03,761
I've broken
some straps.

1007
00:50:03,841 --> 00:50:04,719
Hello?

1008
00:50:06,355 --> 00:50:07,712
Ah, my guests.

1009
00:50:07,792 --> 00:50:08,670
Paul...

1010
00:50:09,867 --> 00:50:11,224
I beg
your pardon?

1011
00:50:11,304 --> 00:50:13,618
I was just saying
hello in Burmese.

1012
00:50:13,698 --> 00:50:14,576
Corie,
ra-vi-shing!

1013
00:50:14,656 --> 00:50:15,853
What does that mean?

1014
00:50:15,932 --> 00:50:17,608
Ravishing.
That's English.

1015
00:50:17,688 --> 00:50:19,045
Ha ha ha ha!

1016
00:50:19,125 --> 00:50:20,961
Paul, would you do
the honors?

1017
00:50:21,040 --> 00:50:23,515
I don't believe you've met Corie's
mother... Mrs. Banks.

1018
00:50:23,595 --> 00:50:25,311
Mom, our new neighbor...
Mr. Velasco.

1019
00:50:25,391 --> 00:50:26,588
How do you do?

1020
00:50:26,668 --> 00:50:29,438
Mrs. Banks, I've been
looking forward so to meeting you.

1021
00:50:29,518 --> 00:50:31,927
I invited your daughter
to my cocktail party,

1022
00:50:32,007 --> 00:50:34,978
and she spent the entire evening
talking of you.

1023
00:50:35,058 --> 00:50:36,946
That must've been
a dull party.

1024
00:50:36,986 --> 00:50:38,230
Not at all.

1025
00:50:38,270 --> 00:50:41,441
I meant talking about me
must've been dull, not the party.

1026
00:50:41,482 --> 00:50:42,887
Ha ha. I understand.

1027
00:50:42,927 --> 00:50:43,851
Thank you.

1028
00:50:43,891 --> 00:50:45,295
Won't you sit down?

1029
00:50:56,737 --> 00:50:57,982
Whishhh!

1030
00:50:58,022 --> 00:50:59,428
Aren't these
marvelous?

1031
00:50:59,468 --> 00:51:01,555
Yes, they're
marvelous.

1032
00:51:02,598 --> 00:51:03,482
And now...

1033
00:51:05,489 --> 00:51:06,373
Knichi!

1034
00:51:06,453 --> 00:51:07,336
Knichi?

1035
00:51:07,416 --> 00:51:08,942
It's an
hors d'oeuvre, Mother.

1036
00:51:09,022 --> 00:51:10,548
Mr. Velasco
makes them himself.

1037
00:51:10,628 --> 00:51:12,314
He's a... a
famous gourmet.

1038
00:51:12,395 --> 00:51:13,439
Gourmet.
Imagine.

1039
00:51:13,519 --> 00:51:16,008
Didn't you once cook for the
king of Sweden?

1040
00:51:16,088 --> 00:51:18,417
Well, we belong to the same
gourmet society.

1041
00:51:18,497 --> 00:51:19,862
150 charter
members,

1042
00:51:19,943 --> 00:51:21,870
including the king,
Prince Philip,

1043
00:51:21,950 --> 00:51:22,873
Fidel Castro.

1044
00:51:22,913 --> 00:51:24,158
Fidel Castro,
too.

1045
00:51:24,198 --> 00:51:26,566
Yes. We meet once
every five years

1046
00:51:26,606 --> 00:51:29,096
for a dinner
we cook ourselves.

1047
00:51:29,176 --> 00:51:32,107
In 1987, they're
supposed to come to my house.

1048
00:51:32,187 --> 00:51:34,235
We have another
30 seconds.

1049
00:51:34,275 --> 00:51:35,198
Till what?

1050
00:51:35,238 --> 00:51:36,643
Until they're
edible.

1051
00:51:36,683 --> 00:51:38,089
The last 15 seconds,

1052
00:51:38,129 --> 00:51:40,497
we just let them
sit there and breathe.

1053
00:51:40,537 --> 00:51:42,545
Oh, Paul,
aren't they gorgeous?

1054
00:51:42,626 --> 00:51:43,749
Yeah.

1055
00:51:43,789 --> 00:51:45,194
When you eat knichi,

1056
00:51:45,235 --> 00:51:47,604
you take a bite
into history.

1057
00:51:47,644 --> 00:51:50,012
Knichi is over
2,000 years old.

1058
